node.text:
Six months ago, I was living in Germany in the state of Rhineland-Palatinate. Less than two weeks ago, the once-in-a-millennium floods ravaged that part of western Germany, killing hundreds of people due to climate change. You probably have seen devastating images of the crisis all over the news. So instead, I want to share some unreleased photos taken in this beautiful region before the destruction.

They're also serve as a reminder to never take what you have for granted, as things can be taken away from you in moment unnoticed.

Let me know which one is your favorite!

node.text:
🐰 🏝 — Located less than a mile off the coast of Kaupo Beach, this islet is truly a sight to behold.  It was once inhabited by rabbits, hence the name Rabbit Island.  Introduced and established by John Cummins in the 1880s when he ran the nearby Waimanalo Plantation, the rabbit colony multiplied for nearly a century.  Sadly, the overpopulation of non-native rabbits wreaked havoc on the native ecosystem, causing them to be eradicated in the late 1990s.

Today, Rabbit Island is designated as a State Seabird Sanctuary & home to more than 10,000 wildlife birds & seals. It is illegal to set foot on this islet without permission from the Hawaii Department of Land and Natural Resources. Good thing I have a drone 😜

node.text:
🥵 As sweltering heat wave sweeping across continental U.S. bringing temperature up to 115°F (46°C); here in Hawaii, it's cool & breezy all year round 🌬️

The reason why Hawaii isn't suffering a heat wave like in mainland is because it's not in the middle of a continent. There isn't a large area of land for hot air to move across before it reaches us. Instead, Hawaii relies on the ocean to moderate its temperatures, which are currently–and just about always–in the mid-80s (27°C), dropping into the 70s (20°C) at night 😌

Don't forget to stay hydrated during this heat! 🥤🥛🍺

node.text:
🇺🇲 Memorial Day | A day to remember 1,170 crew members that were killed on the United States Ship (USS) Arizona during the Japanese attack on the naval base at Pearl Harbor in Hawaii on December 7, 1941. Even 80 years after its demise, USS Arizona continues to spill up to 9 quarts of oil into the harbor each day.

Oil that often coats the surface of the water surrounding the ship has added an emotional gravity for many who visit the memorial and is sometimes referred to as the “tears of the Arizona” or “black tears” 🥺

node.text:
Are you from Prague? Cause I definitely want to Czech you out 😉

One of the most visited square in all of Europe, the Old Town Square is the oldest and most significant square in the historical center of Prague. Its history dates back to the 10th century, when it served as a marketplace at the crossroads of European trade routes.

The square was also a scene of tragic events such as executions, but also various festivals and gatherings of the people throughout the year.

Have you been here before? 😀
.

One of the largest traditional fishing ports in Portugal, the coastal village of Peniche and the sea are inseparable. It was an island until the 16th century when silt created a narrow isthmus. Every summer, surfers worldwide flocked to Peniche to ride the 𝘚𝘶𝘱𝘦𝘳𝘵𝘶𝘣𝘰𝘴, aka the "European Pipeline", after the Banzai Pipeline in Hawaii.

node.text:
Earth, our home planet, is a world unlike any other. 

Deep in the wild California desert, I was stunned to come across a place like no other. Goes by the name of Trona Pinnacles; it was once a lake from approximately 100,000 years ago. These strange rock columns are called tufa towers.  They were formed solely underwater through the mixtures of calcium carbonate & saltwater from underwater springs. It took over centuries for these deposits to gradually grow into towering columns, reaching heights up to 150 feet (45 m). 

From above, the pinnacles look almost extraterrestrial but up close, they’re massively overwhelmed.
